  "proof_sketch": "The mutation changes 'val > 0' to 'val >= 0'. For floating-point inputs, the only bitwise difference occurs when val is exactly negative zero (-0.0): original returns +0.0 (0x00000000), mutant returns -0.0 (0x80000000). Negative zero is representable in float32 and reachable for any element index given the launch parameters (block_size=256, grid_size=1024, size=262144). The tested policies (sparse_extreme, boundary_last_element, etc.) generate zeros as positive zero (+0.0) or avoid zero entirely, so the -0.0 case was never visited.",
  "survival_reason": "The mutation replaces `>` with `>=` in the ReLU kernel. For positive zero, both original and mutant return +0.0 unchanged. For negative zero, the original returns +0.0 (since -0.0 > 0 is false) while the mutant returns -0.0 (since -0.0 >= 0 is true and returns val = -0.0). This creates a bitwise difference. The survival occurred because none of the executed tests ever included a negative zero value in the input tensor. All zero-valued elements in the stress tests were generated as positive zero (e.g., via torch.zeros or masking) and any negative values were strictly less than zero, not exactly -0.0. Therefore the critical boundary condition was missed, and the mutant appeared equivalent under all tested inputs.",
  "killable": true,
  "kill_strategy": "Provide an input tensor of the same fixed shape [16, 16384] and dtype float32 that contains at least one element equal to negative zero (-0.0). This can be achieved by setting a single element to -0.0 and filling the rest with arbitrary values (e.g., random or zeros). The original kernel will output +0.0 for that element, while the mutant will output -0.0, causing a bitwise mismatch.",
  "suggested_test": {
    "description": "Tensor containing a negative zero element to trigger difference between > and >= for zero values",
    "python_code": "def generate_inputs(device):\n    import torch\n    # Create tensor of shape [16, 16384] filled with random floats\n    t = torch.randn(16, 16384, dtype=torch.float32, device=device)\n    # Set the first element to negative zero\n    t[0, 0] = torch.tensor(-0.0, dtype=torch.float32, device=device)\n    return [t]"
  },
  "recommendations": "Add explicit testing of signed zero (negative zero) for relational operator mutations in floating-point kernels. Many mutation testing frameworks overlook the IEEE 754 signed zero semantics, allowing equivalent mutants to survive. Including a dedicated test case with a known -0.0 value closes this coverage gap."
